"""
MKT Context Commentary — Genesis chapters 4–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-genesis-4-6.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/genesis.json (ch6:v5 already present; merge_comm skips it)

Key decisions in this range:
- "Sons of God" (6:2,4) treated with three-interpretation background; not adjudicated
- Nephilim: ANE gibborim/semi-divine hero background noted without endorsing mythology
- Antediluvian lifespans: Sumerian King List parallels noted; literal vs symbolic debate flagged
- Enoch's translation: Second Temple tradition (1 Enoch) referenced briefly
- Lamech's Song (4:23-24): framed as cultural-literary development, not moral endorsement
- Cultural inventions of Cain's line (vv20-22): ANE culture-hero parallels noted
- Ark dimensions: compared to ANE flood parallels (Gilgamesh, Atra-hasis)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

GENESIS_CONTEXT = {
  "4": {
    "1": """<p>Eve's exclamation at Cain's birth — "With the help of the LORD I have brought forth a man" — reflects the Hebrew wordplay between <em>Qayin</em> (Cain) and <em>qānāh</em> (to acquire/create/bring forth). Some ancient interpreters read Eve's words as a messianic expectation: believing Cain might be the promised seed of 3:15 who would crush the serpent. The firstborn son in ANE culture was regarded as the preeminent heir of the family's blessing and destiny; Eve's emphasis on acquiring "a man" (<em>ʾîš</em>, not merely a child) suggests she sees in Cain a full human being of covenant significance. The divine involvement in conception (<em>ʾet-YHWH</em>, with the help of/by YHWH) frames childbirth itself as a theological event.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The name Abel (<em>Heḇel</em>) means "breath/vapor/vanity" — the same word Ecclesiastes deploys as its governing metaphor ("vanity of vanities, all is vanity," Eccl 1:2). The giving of a name meaning "breath" to the second son who is subsequently killed has been read as either ominous foreshadowing or as a common name without weight. The occupational distinction between Abel the shepherd and Cain the farmer mirrors ancient tensions documented across the ANE between pastoral and agricultural communities — the Sumerian <em>Debate between the Shepherd God and the Farmer God</em> (ca. 2000 BCE) dramatizes this rivalry, though in that text the farmer wins. Genesis reverses the expected social hierarchy of settled farmers over nomadic herders by receiving Abel's offering with favor.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>The presentation of first-fruits as an offering was universal in the ancient Near East — both to deities (temple offerings) and to ruling overlords (tribute). The Hebrew word <em>minḥāh</em> (offering/tribute) used for Cain's grain offering is the standard term for the grain/tribute offering in the Levitical system (Lev 2). The phrase "in the course of time" (<em>miqṣēt yāmîm</em>, at the end of days) suggests an established agricultural cycle — harvest-time — rather than a spontaneous impulse. The absence of detail about <em>what</em> Cain brought (contrast Abel's "fat portions from the firstborn") has generated interpretive debate: was Cain's offering deficient in quality, attitude, or category?</p>""",
    "4": """<p>Abel brought "fat portions from the firstborn (<em>mibĕḵōrôt</em>) of his flock" — two precise specifications: the firstborn animal (which belonged to YHWH by right, Exod 13:2; Num 18:17) and the fat portions (<em>ḥēlḇ</em>), which later Levitical law reserved exclusively for YHWH (Lev 3:16-17: "all the fat is YHWH's"). Abel's offering anticipates the very criteria that the sacrificial system will formalize. The LORD's "regard" (<em>wayyašaʿ</em>, Hiphil of <em>šāʿāh</em> — to gaze/look with favor) echoes the priestly blessing formula of Num 6:25 ("the LORD make his face shine on you") — the divine gaze of acceptance is the highest covenant-gift.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>Cain's response — "his face fell" (<em>nāplû pānāyw</em>) — is an idiom for public shame and loss of honor. The phrase appears in Jer 3:12 for the humiliation of apostasy and in Job 29:24 for condescension. In the ANE honor-shame culture, a "fallen face" signaled not merely sadness but social disgrace — the outward expression of a compromised standing before the community. Cain's anger (<em>wayyiḥar</em>, "it burned hot") is described before any act of violence: the narrative locates the first murder's origin in the interior disposition of unchanneled rage and humiliation.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>YHWH's dialogue with Cain before the murder is unique in the early Genesis narratives — a direct divine pastoral engagement with a person on the verge of sin. The rhetorical questions ("Why are you angry? Why is your face downcast?") are the same interrogative-accountability pattern established in 3:9 ("Where are you?"). YHWH does not condemn Cain's anger as inherently sinful but invites self-examination — the anger is a symptom addressable through right action. The divine approach here is therapeutic before it becomes judicial.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The personification of sin as a crouching predator — "sin is crouching (<em>rōḇēṣ</em>) at your door; it desires (<em>tĕšûqātô</em>) to have you, but you must rule over it" — is a striking ANE image. <em>Rāḇaṣ</em> (to crouch/lie in wait) describes the posture of an animal ready to pounce; the same root appears in the Babylonian demon <em>Rabisu</em> ("the croucher"), a malicious spirit that lurked at doorways and thresholds waiting to attack the unwary. The word <em>tĕšûqāh</em> (desire/longing — used for the woman's desire for the husband in 3:16 and the Beloved's desire in Song 7:10) is applied here to sin's dominating desire for Cain. The echo of 3:16 is deliberate: as the man was told he would "rule over" the woman, Cain is now told he must rule over sin — and fails.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>The MT of v8 contains a well-known textual gap: "Cain said to his brother Abel" — and then nothing before "while they were in the field." The Samaritan Pentateuch, LXX, Peshitta, and Vulgate all supply "Let us go out to the field" to fill the ellipsis. This is one of the clearest cases in the Pentateuch where early versions preserve a reading that seems necessary for narrative coherence. The field (<em>śādeh</em>) as the murder-site is significant: it is the agricultural domain Cain worked, away from human witnesses. The same isolation is used for other ANE ambush narratives (Deut 22:25-27: an ambush in the field where no one hears the cry for help).</p>""",
    "9": """<p>Cain's response to YHWH's question — "Am I my brother's keeper (<em>šōmēr</em>)?" — inverts the very vocation established in 2:15 where <em>šāmar</em> (to guard/keep) described Adam's priestly care of the garden-sanctuary. The keeper-vocation of the image-bearer is denied in the most blunt terms possible. The question has been read in rabbinic tradition as the founding statement of the denial of social responsibility — the refusal to be accountable for the well-being of one's neighbor. The Mishnah's commentary on this verse (Sanhedrin 4:5) derives from it the principle that each person's life contains an entire world.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>"Your brother's blood (<em>dāmê</em>) cries out (<em>ṣōʿăqîm</em>) to me from the ground" — the Hebrew plural "bloods" (<em>dāmîm</em>, literally "bloods") was interpreted by the rabbis (Mishnah Sanhedrin 4:5) as referring to Abel and all his potential descendants: Cain did not merely kill one person but all who might have descended from him. The concept of blood "crying out" for justice is deeply embedded in ANE legal culture: the blood of the unavenged dead was thought to pollute the land and demand retribution (cf. Job 16:18: "O earth, do not cover my blood"; Isa 26:21; Ezek 24:7-8). The ground that received Abel's blood now becomes the plaintive witness against the murderer.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>Cain's curse intensifies Adam's curse of 3:17: where the ground was cursed to resist Adam's labor in general, the ground now specifically refuses to yield for Cain who used it as a site of murder. The ground "opened its mouth" (<em>pāʿăṯāh ʾet-pîhā</em>) to receive Abel's blood — the earth as a passive but implicated instrument of the crime now becomes an active witness against the perpetrator. This idea of the land as morally participant in human action runs throughout the prophetic literature: the land "vomits out" those who defile it with blood and injustice (Lev 18:25,28; Num 35:33-34).</p>""",
    "12": """<p>The sentence of being "a restless wanderer" (<em>nāʿ wānāḏ</em>) on the earth defines Cain's existence as the inverse of settled agricultural life. In Mesopotamian literature, the Amorites and other semi-nomadic groups were described in condescending terms: "who knows no grain, who has never known a city, who does not bend his knee, who eats raw meat." To be landless and wandering was the lowest possible social condition in ANE agrarian civilization. The double <em>nāʿ wānāḏ</em> (restless-wandering) is a sound-echo pairing that intensifies the sentence through repetition and alliteration.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>Cain's response "my punishment is more than I can bear" (<em>gāḏôl ʿăwônî minnĕśōʾ</em>) uses the word <em>ʿāwôn</em>, which carries the double meaning of "iniquity/guilt" and "punishment/consequence" — the same semantic range as Hebrew's covenant-violation vocabulary throughout the OT. Cain's complaint is simultaneously "my guilt is too great to be forgiven" and "my punishment is too great to be endured" — both meanings are present. The tradition of divine mercy that will follow (vv14-15) addresses both dimensions: protection from the punishment and a future implicit possibility of relationship restoration.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>Cain's fear — "whoever finds me will kill me" — presupposes an existing population of human beings against whom he might need protection. The narrative assumes the reader understands that Adam and Eve have other children beyond Cain and Abel (5:4: "Adam had other sons and daughters"). The blood-vengeance obligation in ANE law was carried by the <em>gō ʾēl haddām</em> (avenger of blood) — the nearest kinsman who was legally required to pursue and execute the killer of a relative (Num 35:19-21; Deut 19:6,12). Cain's expulsion from the protection of the family/community creates genuine mortal danger.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>The "mark of Cain" — YHWH set "a sign (<em>ʾôt</em>) on Cain so that no one who found him would kill him" — is one of the most discussed details in Genesis. The text does not describe the mark's nature; ancient and modern interpreters have proposed everything from a divine tattoo to a physical feature to an assigned bodyguard. The mark is protective, not stigmatic — it functions like a divine protection-seal. The "sevenfold" (<em>šiḇʿātayim</em>) vengeance promised against Cain's killer echoes the ANE concept of multiplied retribution for attacking one under divine protection. That YHWH extends such protection to a murderer is a demonstration of mercy within the framework of covenant justice.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>The "land of Nod" (<em>ʾereṣ-nôḏ</em>) is a place-name derived from the same root as "wandering" (<em>nûḏ/nāḏ</em>), the same root in Cain's sentence of v12 — the "land of wandering" is named for the condition of its first inhabitant. "East of Eden" echoes the direction of expulsion in 3:24 (cherubim placed on the east side of Eden) — to go "east of Eden" is to move progressively further from the divine presence, a geographic metaphor for spiritual distance that recurs in Genesis (Babel also moves eastward, 11:2).</p>""",
    "17": """<p>Cain's city-building is the first recorded human act of civilization-creation in the exiled line. In Mesopotamian tradition, kingship and city-building were closely linked: the Sumerian King List records that kingship "descended from heaven" and was associated with the first great cities (Eridu, Uruk, Larsa). The naming of a city after one's son was standard ANE practice for establishing dynastic territorial claims — e.g., Ramesses II naming a city Ramesse. Cain's city named "Enoch" (<em>Ḥănôḵ</em>, meaning "dedicated/initiated") is the first specifically urban human community — civilization emerging in the exiled line, not in the covenant line.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>The genealogy of Cain (vv17-22) is a genealogy of cultural origination — each descendant is named as the founder of a domain of human civilization. The names in the Cainite genealogy have suggestive parallels with the Sethite genealogy of ch5: Enoch/Enosh, Irad/Jared, Methushael/Methuselah, Lamech/Lamech. Whether this is coincidence, shared name-pool, or deliberate narrative structure is debated. The parallel genealogies may be variants of a common ancestral tradition differently shaped by the two narrative trajectories.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>Lamech's marriage to two women — Adah and Zillah — is the first recorded instance of polygamy in the Bible. It appears in the Cainite line, without authorial comment, as part of the cultural development of the exiled community. The creation-norm of one man and one woman (2:24) is here implicitly departed from. The patriarchal narratives will later show the strife produced by polygamous households (Rachel and Leah; Sarah and Hagar); the Deuteronomic law explicitly warns the king against "many wives" (Deut 17:17). The practice is described, not endorsed.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>Jabal is named as "the father (<em>ʾāḇ</em>) of those who live in tents and raise livestock" — the phrase "father of" is the ANE idiom for "founder/originator of a way of life." The Mesopotamian <em>Apkallu</em> (seven antediluvian sages) were similarly credited with originating the arts of civilization before the flood: Uanna (Oannes) brought writing and architecture; other sages brought metallurgy, music, and animal husbandry. Genesis attributes these same cultural origins to human initiative within Cain's line, without the divine-sage intermediary of the Babylonian tradition.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>Jubal is "the father of all who play stringed instruments and pipes" — the <em>kinnôr</em> (lyre/harp) and <em>ʿûgāḇ</em> (pipe/flute). The <em>kinnôr</em> was David's instrument (1 Sam 16:23; 2 Sam 6:5), used in the temple worship; it also appeared in the worship of other ANE deities (Egyptian temple scenes depict harps and pipes in divine worship). The attribution of music to the Cainite line — before the flood, outside the covenant community — establishes music as a broadly human cultural achievement, not a specifically covenant gift. The cultural achievements of fallen humanity are real gifts, even if their origin lies in the exiled line.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>Tubal-Cain "forged all kinds of tools out of bronze and iron" — the name Tubal-Cain has been connected with the smithing traditions of the people of Tubal in Asia Minor (Ezek 27:13; 38:2-3) and with Vulcan/Hephaestus in classical tradition (a cross-cultural smith-deity). Metal-working was among the most transformative technologies of the ancient world: the Bronze Age (ca. 3300-1200 BCE) and Iron Age (ca. 1200-550 BCE) are named for their dominant metal technologies. The mastery of iron-working in particular provided military superiority. The attribution of metallurgy to the pre-flood Cainite line explains the cultural technology that humanity possesses after the flood.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>Lamech's "Song of the Sword" (vv23-24) is the first extended poetry attributed to a human being (after Adam's recognition speech in 2:23). Addressed to his two wives, it boasts of unlimited retribution: "I have killed a man for wounding me, a young man for injuring me." The poetic form — paired couplets in synonymous parallelism — shows developed literary culture. The song transforms Cain's protective mark (sevenfold vengeance, v15) into a personal boast of infinite personal vengeance (77-fold). The escalation from YHWH's covenant-protection (sevenfold) to human self-assertion (77-fold) illustrates the moral trajectory of the Cainite line: each generation amplifies the culture of violence.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>The 77-fold vengeance claim inverts the covenant-community pattern: YHWH's protection of the vulnerable will later climax in Jesus's teaching that forgiveness should be extended "seventy-seven times" (Matt 18:22) — a direct echo and inversion of Lamech's boast. Where Lamech multiplies retribution seventy-sevenfold, Jesus multiplies forgiveness seventy-sevenfold. The Genesis narrative establishes the cultural logic that Christ's teaching will reverse: the civilization that maximizes vengeance is the inverse of the kingdom that maximizes forgiveness.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>Seth's naming — "God has set/appointed for me another seed (<em>zeraʿ</em>) in place of Abel" — uses the covenant-seed language of 3:15. The word <em>zeraʿ</em> (seed/offspring) is the same term from the protoevangelium; Eve names Seth as the continuation of the promised seed-line. The name Seth (<em>Šēṯ</em>) from <em>šîṯ</em> (to set/place) means "placed/appointed" — a divinely-appointed replacement. The narrative structure of ch4 closes with the renewal of hope through a new line: Cain/violence moves east toward Nod; Seth continues the covenant trajectory.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>The closing note — "At that time people began to call on the name of the LORD" (<em>liqqrōʾ bĕšēm YHWH</em>) — marks the beginning of formal covenant worship in the line of Seth. The phrase "call on the name of YHWH" becomes the standard idiom for covenantal worship and prayer throughout the OT: Abraham calls on YHWH's name at Bethel (12:8) and Beersheba (26:25); Elijah's contest on Carmel turns on who can call on their god's name (1 Kgs 18:24). The worship community that traces from Seth through Enosh is the progenitor of Israel's covenantal worship tradition, in explicit contrast to the city-building, culture-developing Cainite line.</p>"""
  },
  "5": {
    "1": """<p>The tenth <em>tôlĕḏôt</em> formula ("This is the written account of Adam's family line") opens the antediluvian genealogy with a deliberate echo of 1:26-27 — "When God created mankind, he made them in the likeness of God." Despite the Fall of ch3, the <em>ṣelem</em>/<em>dĕmût</em> (image/likeness) language is explicitly restated as still operative. The image of God in humanity was not obliterated by sin; Gen 9:6 will confirm it remains the basis for the prohibition of murder. The genealogy begins with the reaffirmation of the divine image because it will trace a line through fallen, mortal humanity to a flood — and the image-bearers who die throughout are not merely expendable statistics.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The summary of ch1:27 — "he created them male and female and blessed them" — restates the creation mandate within the genealogical framework, establishing that the antediluvian genealogy is the fulfillment of the fruitfulness blessing. "He named them 'Mankind' (<em>ʾādām</em>)" — God's naming of the human race as a whole echoes the naming-as-sovereignty pattern of ch1 (vv5,8,10). The collective name <em>ʾādām</em> encompasses all humanity in one named entity before the genealogy differentiates individuals — every individual in the list participates in the collective divine image-naming.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>The genealogical formula reaches its theological core in v3: Adam's son Seth is described as being born "in his own likeness, in his own image" — the same vocabulary (<em>dĕmût / ṣelem</em>) used for humanity's creation in the divine image (1:26). The theological implication is dual: the image of God is transmitted generationally, but through a fallen parent. What Seth inherits is both the divine image-bearing dignity and the fallen nature of post-Eden humanity. Augustine's doctrine of original sin finds its foundational text here: children inherit the likeness of their parents, including the spiritual consequences of the Fall.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The formula "Adam lived 800 years and had other sons and daughters" is the genealogy's standard secondary notation. The reference to "other sons and daughters" confirms that Adam's family was large, explaining the population presupposed in ch4 (Cain's fear of being killed; Cain building a city). The genealogical register omits these other children — only the direct covenant-line is traced. This selectivity is characteristic of ANE and biblical genealogies: the purpose is to trace a specific lineage, not to document an entire family tree.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>The refrain "and then he died" (<em>wayyāmot</em>) sounds for the first time in v5 and will repeat for every patriarch in the list (except Enoch, v24). The death-refrain is the genealogy's structural heartbeat: each life, however long, ends with the fulfillment of the death-warning of 2:17. The extreme lifespans — Adam 930 years — have close parallels in the Sumerian King List, which records antediluvian kings reigning for 28,800 to 36,000 years (clearly symbolic or astronomical numbers). The Genesis lifespans are dramatically shorter than the Sumerian parallels but follow the same pattern: extremely long pre-flood lives followed by dramatically shortened post-flood lives. Whether the numbers are literal, representative of tribal/dynastic generations, or use a different counting system remains debated.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>The formulaic genealogical entry for Seth traces the direct covenant-line from Adam. Seth's 105-year lifespan before Enosh's birth is part of the decreasing-with-each-generation pattern that characterizes the genealogy — the antediluvian patriarchs' first-born ages at fatherhood are variable but their total lifespans cluster between 895 and 969 years. The names in the Sethite line (Enosh, Kenan, Mahalalel, Jared, Enoch, Methuselah, Lamech, Noah) were preserved in Jewish tradition as the great pre-flood righteous figures; several appear in later Second Temple literature as bearers of divine revelation.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The secondary formula "Seth lived 807 years and had other sons and daughters" follows the genealogy's standard pattern for the years after the birth of the named heir. The genealogy's focus on the named covenant-line child while acknowledging other offspring follows the ANE practice of selective genealogy — the genealogy serves to establish a specific line of descent, not to census the entire population. The total lifespan of 912 years places Seth within the top tier of antediluvian longevity.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>Enosh's name (<em>ʾĕnôš</em>) is a synonym for <em>ʾādām</em> — both mean "human being/man," with <em>ʾĕnôš</em> carrying a connotation of frailty and mortality (cf. Ps 8:4: "What is <em>ʾĕnôš</em> that you are mindful of him?"; Job 4:17: "Can a mortal/<em>ʾĕnôš</em> be more righteous than God?"). The name at this point in the genealogy — just after the beginning of formal worship (4:26: "at that time people began to call on the name of YHWH") — creates an implicit tension: the frail, mortal human creature is the one who calls on the eternal God.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>Kenan's name (<em>Qênān</em>) may be related to <em>Qayin</em> (Cain) — pointing to the shadowy doubling between the Cainite and Sethite genealogies noted by scholars. The parallel names in the two genealogies (Enoch/Enosh, Irad/Jared, Methushael/Methuselah, Lamech/Lamech) suggest either a common name-pool or a deliberate structural mirroring. The genealogy's purpose is not to solve this puzzle but to establish the unbroken succession of the covenant-seed line from Adam to Noah.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>Enosh's 815 post-Kenan years and total 905-year lifespan follow the genealogy's standard decreasing secondary pattern. The gradually shifting numbers across the genealogy — each patriarch's first-birth age and total lifespan are individually specified — suggest the numbers were carefully transmitted and not simply repeated. Ancient readers familiar with Mesopotamian genealogical lists would have found the specificity reassuring: the pre-flood lineage was a documented record, not a vague tradition.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>The formulaic "Altogether, Enosh lived a total of 905 years, and then he died" marks the second sounding of the death-refrain. In the context of the genealogy's overall structure, these deaths are not narrative tragedies but theological punctuation marks — each life, however long, is bracketed by birth and death, confirming the mortality-within-dignity of the image-bearing creature. The repetition also creates a liturgical-like rhythm that ancient oral recitation would have reinforced: the genealogy was likely recited in formal contexts, its regular cadence part of its religious function.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>Kenan's 70-year lifespan before Mahalalel's birth is the shortest first-birth age in the genealogy (the others range from 65 to 187 years). Mahalalel's name means "praise of God" or "God is praised" (<em>māhalal</em> = praise + <em>ʾēl</em> = God) — the first theophoric name in the Sethite genealogy, embedding a theology of praise directly into the covenant-line's naming practice.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>The secondary formula for Kenan — 840 years after Mahalalel's birth — places Kenan's total at 910 years, in the central range of the antediluvian patriarchs. The function of the genealogy in its ANE context was to establish the antiquity and legitimacy of the covenant-line: the extreme lifespans are evidence of a blessed and divinely-sustained lineage reaching back to creation itself. No other ancient tradition could claim an unbroken line of such length — the genealogy is a covenant-identity document.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The death of Kenan at 910 years is the fourth sounding of the genealogy's death-refrain. The cumulative effect of four deaths in close succession (Adam, Seth, Enosh, Kenan) establishes an irresistible pattern before the exception of Enoch in v24 will shatter it. The narrative architecture is deliberate: the reader is being conditioned by repetition to expect "and then he died" so that "he was no more, because God took him" will register as the rupture it is.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>Mahalalel's 65-year lifespan before Jared's birth is the second-shortest first-birth age in the genealogy, matching Enoch's age at Methuselah's birth (v21). Jared's name may derive from <em>yārad</em> (to descend) — the name is sometimes connected in later Jewish tradition with the "descent" of the Watchers (the angelic beings of 6:1-4) during Jared's lifetime, as developed in 1 Enoch. The connection is speculative but illustrates how later interpreters read the genealogy as encoding the timeline of the supernatural events that led to the flood.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>Mahalalel's secondary lifespan of 830 years (total: 895 years) places him at the lower end of the antediluvian patriarchs' longevity. The systematic recording of these secondary years — years lived after the birth of the covenant-line heir — serves a chronological function: the genealogy allows ancient readers to calculate the total span from Adam to the flood, which the internal Genesis chronology places at 1,656 years. This kind of precise chronological genealogy is paralleled in Mesopotamian king-lists, which similarly serve as chronological anchors for understanding the relationship between the present and the primordial past.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>The death of Mahalalel at 895 years is the fifth death-refrain in the genealogy. The cumulative death-toll before Enoch creates an unmistakable theological meditation on mortality: even the longest lives in human history all end the same way. The rabbinic tradition of reading ch5 as a meditation on human transience and the need for righteous living within finite time reflects the text's own insistence: no matter how long the patriarch lived, "and then he died" concludes the account.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>Jared's 162-year lifespan before Enoch's birth is one of the longer first-birth ages in the genealogy (only Methuselah at 187 is longer). The name Jared (<em>Yereḏ</em>) — from the root "to descend" — embedded the tradition of cosmic descent within the genealogical name. 1 Enoch, the Second Temple Jewish pseudepigraphon attributed to the next figure in the line, explicitly names the Watchers' descent during the days of Jared (1 Enoch 6:6), suggesting an early interpretive tradition that saw Jared's era as the era of the supernatural intermarriage described in 6:1-4.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>Jared's 800 post-Enoch years give him a total of 962 years — the second-longest lifespan in the genealogy after Methuselah's 969. The secondary-years formula for each patriarch establishes the genealogy's double function: tracing the covenant-line (the named firstborn) and documenting the extended family (other sons and daughters). The "other sons and daughters" clauses are a consistent reminder that the genealogy is selective: the covenant-line is one thread in a much larger family tapestry.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>Jared's death at 962 years is the sixth death-refrain, one before the genealogy's structural climax. The narrative rhythm has now established the unbroken pattern so firmly that the next entry — Enoch's — will break it with maximum impact. The reader's expectation of "and then he died" is the literary preparation for "God took him." The genealogy is building to its theological apex through deliberate, repetitive conditioning.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>Enoch's 65-year lifespan before Methuselah's birth is the shortest first-birth age in the genealogy (tied with Mahalalel at v15). The name Enoch (<em>Ḥănôḵ</em>) means "dedicated/initiated" — the same name as Cain's city in 4:17, the first entry in the Cainite line. The Sethite Enoch mirrors and contrasts the Cainite city: the city in Cain's line represents civilization built apart from God; the person Enoch in Seth's line represents the closest possible human walk with God. The identical name creates a structural contrast between the two lines' representatives of human development.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>Enoch's post-Methuselah life is described uniquely: he "walked faithfully with God 300 years." The Hebrew <em>wayyithallek Ḥănôḵ ʾet-hāʾĕlōhîm</em> (Enoch walked with God) uses the same Hithpael form as YHWH's "walking in the garden" in 3:8 — the intimate garden-communion that Adam forfeited is recovered by Enoch. "Walked with God" is applied to only two antediluvian figures: Enoch (5:22-24) and Noah (6:9). In the ANE context, the figure of the <em>apkallu</em> (sage) who lived before the flood and enjoyed special divine knowledge was well-established; Enoch functions as Israel's equivalent — a sage who walked in divine intimacy without the mythology of divine-human ancestry.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>Enoch's total lifespan of 365 years is conspicuously the shortest in the genealogy and numerically equal to the solar year. The solar symbolism has not been lost on interpreters ancient or modern: Enoch lived one year for every day of the year. Whether this is coincidence or deliberate numerology is unknown. What is certain is that the brevity of his years against the backdrop of the genealogy's 895-969-year lifespans heightens the paradox of his translation: the one who walked most closely with God lived the fewest years of any patriarch in the list.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>The genealogy's structural rupture: "Enoch walked faithfully with God; then he was no more, because God took him away (<em>wayyiqqaḥ ʾōtô ʾĕlōhîm</em>)." The death-refrain is absent — this is the genealogy's sole exception after seven identical entries. "God took him" uses the same verb (<em>lāqaḥ</em>) as Elijah's later translation (2 Kgs 2:3,5,9-10: "YHWH is going to take your master from you today"). In Second Temple Judaism, Enoch became the premier figure of heavenly-journey apocalyptic literature: 1 Enoch (preserved in full in Ethiopic) elaborates his heavenly visions, his role as cosmic scribe, and his encounters with divine secrets. Heb 11:5 cites his translation as an act of faith; Jude 14-15 quotes from 1 Enoch, showing the tradition's currency in NT-era Judaism.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>Methuselah's 187-year lifespan before Lamech's birth is the longest first-birth age in the genealogy. The name Methuselah (<em>Mĕtûšelaḥ</em>) may mean "man of the javelin/dart" or, in a popular etymology, "his death shall bring" — which, if intentional, would be consistent with Methuselah's death in the year of the flood according to internal chronological calculation (he lived 969 years; the flood came 600 years after Noah's birth in Lamech's 777th year). The internal chronology of the genealogy appears to have been constructed so that Methuselah dies precisely in the flood year — though without surviving the flood.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>Methuselah's 782 post-Lamech years give him the genealogy's longest total lifespan: 969 years. The numerical specificity across the genealogy — no two patriarchs share identical first-birth ages or total lifespans — suggests intentional differentiation rather than schematic repetition. Ancient readers would have noticed Methuselah's record-setting longevity; the phrase "old as Methuselah" has entered English as the proverbial expression of extreme age. The genealogy's numbers were clearly transmitted as significant and distinguishable, not merely as round-number approximations.</p>""",
    "27": """<p>Methuselah's death at 969 years is the record lifespan in the genealogy and the last death-refrain before the anomalous Enoch (whose death the formula skips). The regularity of "and then he died" through eight entries (Adam, Seth, Enosh, Kenan, Mahalalel, Jared, Methuselah, Lamech) brackets the Enoch exception and resumes after it, confirming that Enoch's non-death was the intended structural highlight. Death is the universal human condition; Enoch's exception is the exception that proves the rule — and provides a glimpse of what the curse's reversal would look like.</p>""",
    "28": """<p>Lamech's 182-year lifespan before Noah's birth continues the pattern of relatively long first-birth ages in the later generations of the genealogy. The naming of Noah in v29 will carry the genealogy's most explicit messianic-expectation language: the patriarch whose name means "rest/comfort" is given explicit eschatological freight by his father's hope. In the ANE context of the Sumerian King List, the flood-hero (Ziusudra/Utnapishtim) similarly stands at the end of a long pre-flood genealogical sequence before the flood narrative begins — Genesis employs the same structural architecture while filling it with theologically distinctive content.</p>""",
    "29": """<p>Lamech's naming of Noah — "He will comfort us in the labor and painful toil of our hands caused by the ground the LORD has cursed" — is the genealogy's only extended comment, signaling the naming as theologically weighted. The wordplay: Noah (<em>Nōaḥ</em>) from <em>nāḥam</em> (to comfort/rest) or <em>nûaḥ</em> (to rest) — the root that gives us the Sabbath-rest (<em>nûaḥ</em>) and the "resting place" of the Ark (8:4: the ark "rested" on Ararat). Lamech's hope that Noah will "comfort us" against the curse of 3:17 is a proto-messianic expectation: Noah will not ultimately remove the curse, but his covenant-relationship with YHWH will create the new-creation conditions of the post-flood world (9:1-17).</p>""",
    "30": """<p>Lamech's 595 post-Noah years are notably shorter than his forebears' secondary years, reflecting the genealogy's overall pattern of gradually declining secondary lifespans as the flood approaches. Total lifespan: 777 years — a symbolically significant number (seven is the number of completeness; 777 is a tripling). In contrast to Lamech of Cain's line (4:23-24) — whose song boasted of 77-fold vengeance — this Lamech dies at 777 years and names a son who will bring comfort. The two Lameches are the genealogies' paired representatives: violence vs. comfort, vengeance vs. rest.</p>""",
    "31": """<p>Lamech's death at 777 years precedes the flood by five years (if Noah was 600 at the flood, and Lamech died when Noah was 595). The death-refrain's return after Lamech confirms that the Enoch exception was the only exception: even the father of the flood-hero dies in the ordinary human way. Noah alone, like Enoch before him, will experience an extraordinary divine preservation — not translation but covenant-deliverance through the waters.</p>""",
    "32": """<p>Noah's fathering of Shem, Ham, and Japheth at "after he was 500 years old" closes the Sethite genealogy with the three sons who will repopulate the earth after the flood. Unlike every previous patriarchal entry, Noah's is not followed by a secondary lifespan and death notice here — instead ch6 opens immediately with the events leading to the flood. The three sons will become the ancestors of the Table of Nations in ch10: Shem (ancestor of Semitic peoples, including Israel), Ham (ancestor of African and Canaanite peoples), Japheth (ancestor of Indo-European peoples). The genealogy that began with one man (Adam) ends with one man's three sons about to become humanity's new source.</p>"""
  },
  "6": {
    "1": """<p>The opening of ch6 — "When human beings began to increase in number on the earth and daughters were born to them" — sets the scene for the most contested passage in Genesis. The increase of human population after the Fall is a fulfillment of the creation mandate (1:28: "be fruitful and multiply") but in the context of universal wickedness (6:5) becomes the precondition for judgment rather than blessing. The ANE flood tradition in the <em>Atra-hasis</em> epic similarly begins with the gods being disturbed by human population growth and noise before deciding to send the flood — Genesis reverses the rationale: the problem is not human noise but human wickedness.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The "sons of God" (<em>bĕnê hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) who take human wives is the most debated passage in Genesis. Three main interpretive traditions: (1) <em>Divine beings</em>: <em>bĕnê hāʾĕlōhîm</em> in Job 1:6; 2:1; 38:7 consistently refers to heavenly beings/angels; the pre-Christian Jewish tradition (1 Enoch 6-11; Jubilees 5; the Dead Sea Scrolls) unanimously identifies them as fallen angelic Watchers; 2 Pet 2:4 and Jude 6 allude to this tradition. (2) <em>Sethite line</em>: the sons of God = righteous descendants of Seth marrying daughters of Cain's line — common in patristic and Reformed interpretation, avoiding supernatural beings. (3) <em>Dynastic rulers</em>: ANE kings routinely claimed divine sonship; the passage may describe tyrant-kings (<em>gibbôrîm</em>, v4) taking multiple wives by coercive power. The divine-being interpretation best fits the word usage elsewhere, but the seriousness of the interpretive debate should not be minimized.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>YHWH's declaration "My Spirit will not contend with humans forever, for they are mortal; their days will be a hundred and twenty years" is textually difficult. The word translated "contend" (<em>yāḏôn</em>, hapax legomenon) may also mean "abide/remain in." The 120-year limit may refer either to a lifespan limit on humans or to the remaining time before the flood — 120 years as Noah's construction timeline. The <em>Atra-hasis</em> epic similarly records divine deliberations about limiting human lifespan and population before the flood, though by different means. YHWH's declaration here establishes a divine timeline within which Noah will build and warn.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The Nephilim (<em>nĕpîlîm</em>) — "those who fall upon" or "the fallen ones" — are described as the offspring of the divine-being/human unions, and as "heroes (<em>gibbôrîm</em>) of old, men of renown (<em>ʾanšê haššēm</em>)." <em>Gibbôr</em> means mighty warrior/hero; <em>ʾanšê haššēm</em> (men of the name/renown) is the language of fame-seeking that Babel will later attempt (11:4: "let us make a name for ourselves"). In ANE tradition, semi-divine heroes were a recognized category: Gilgamesh was described as "two-thirds divine, one-third human"; the Akkadian <em>apkallu</em>-sages were semi-divine culture-heroes. Genesis acknowledges the cultural phenomenon without endorsing the mythology — these figures existed, they were mighty, and their existence is connected to the corruption that necessitated the flood.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>The divine response to universal human wickedness — "The LORD regretted (<em>wayyinnāḥem</em>) that he had made human beings on the earth, and his heart was deeply troubled (<em>wayyitʿaṣṣēḇ</em>)" — uses strongly anthropomorphic language for divine emotion. The word <em>nāḥam</em> (to relent/regret/comfort) can mean both "to be grieved/sorry" and "to relent from a decision." The same root names Noah (5:29: "He will comfort/<em>nāḥam</em> us"), creating a wordplay: the one who will bring the post-flood comfort is born into the world that causes YHWH's <em>nāḥam</em> (grief). The ANE flood traditions similarly describe the gods being troubled by humanity (in <em>Atra-hasis</em>, by the noise/clamor); Genesis substitutes a moral rationale for an existential one.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The decree to "wipe (<em>ʾemḥeh</em>) from the face of the earth" the entirety of animate creation — humans, animals, birds, ground-creatures — is the un-creation of days 5-6. The same comprehensive scope (<em>kol-ḥayyat hāʾăḏāmāh</em>, every living thing on the ground) that was blessed in 1:20-28 will be blotted out. The verb <em>māḥāh</em> (to wipe/blot out) is used for wiping out a name from a book (Exod 32:32-33) and for erasing sin (Ps 51:9). The flood is presented as a divine erasure of the corrupted creation, preparing for a new beginning — the same structure as the original creation from chaos.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>The structural pivot: "But Noah found favor (<em>ḥēn</em>) in the eyes of the LORD." <em>Ḥēn</em> (grace/favor) is the quintessential covenant-grace term — it describes a disposition of goodwill that is given, not earned. The same formula recurs for Moses (Exod 33:12-13), Gideon (Judg 6:17), and others who receive YHWH's particular favor. The structural contrast between vv7 and 8 is stark: universal decree of destruction → one man's grace. This pattern — judgment with one righteous exception — will recur in Sodom (Lot) and Jericho (Rahab). Noah's grace is the narrative hinge on which the flood narrative turns.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>The three-term description of Noah's character — "righteous (<em>ṣaddîq</em>), blameless (<em>tāmîm</em>) among the people of his time, and he walked faithfully with God (<em>ʾet-hāʾĕlōhîm hithallēk</em>)" — is the most comprehensive character commendation in Genesis to this point. <em>Ṣaddîq</em> (righteous) is the covenant-standing term; <em>tāmîm</em> (blameless/wholehearted) is the sacrificial standard applied to unblemished animals (Exod 12:5; Lev 1:3) and to Abraham's called-to-be-blameless standard (17:1). "Walked with God" echoes Enoch's description (5:22,24) — the pre-Fall garden-communion language. "Among the people of his time" (<em>bĕḏōrōtāyw</em>) introduces a note of comparative evaluation: righteous <em>in his generation</em> — a qualification the rabbinic tradition debated (was Noah righteous relative only to his corrupt contemporaries, or absolutely?)</p>""",
    "10": """<p>The <em>tôlĕḏôt</em> formula opening (v9: "This is the account of Noah and his family") and the immediate listing of Noah's three sons (Shem, Ham, Japheth) follow the standard genealogical introduction pattern of Genesis. The three sons are named in v10 in an order that does not reflect birth order (Shem is the oldest, but Ham will be addressed first in the moral crisis of 9:20-25; Japheth is the youngest). The three-son structure mirrors the three-line humanity of the post-flood world: the Table of Nations (ch10) will trace all peoples to one of the three.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>"The earth was corrupt (<em>tišāḥēt</em>) in God's sight and was full of violence (<em>ḥāmās</em>)." Both terms carry specific legal and prophetic weight. <em>Šāḥat</em> (corrupt/ruin/destroy) is the verbal root for moral and social corruption throughout the prophetic literature (Ezek 16:47; 20:44; Mal 1:14 — "corrupted animal offering"). <em>Ḥāmās</em> (violence/injustice/wrong) is the specific word for structural social violence throughout the prophets: Amos (3:10), Micah (6:12), Habakkuk (1:2-3; 2:8,17), and Ezekiel (7:11,23; 8:17) all use <em>ḥāmās</em> for the violence that provokes divine judgment. The pre-flood world is diagnosed in precisely the terms the prophets will use for Israel's eventual exile.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>"God saw (<em>wayyarʾ</em>) how corrupt the earth had become" — the same verb used in the creation week's "God saw that it was good" (1:4,10,12,18,21,25,31) is now used for the inverse perception: God sees the corruption rather than the goodness. The creation-narrative reversal is deliberate: the creation that God saw as "very good" (1:31) has been corrupted by "all the people on earth" (<em>kol-bāśār</em>, all flesh). The comprehensive corruption is total: "all flesh had corrupted its way" (<em>kî-hišḥît kol-bāśār ʾet-darkô</em>) — the same verb used in v11's "corrupt," now applied reflexively: flesh corrupted itself.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>"The earth is filled with violence (<em>ḥāmās</em>) because of them" — YHWH's diagnostic includes a causal statement: the violence fills the earth "because of them" (<em>mippĕnêhem</em>, literally "from before their face/presence"). Human violence is the specific cause of the judgment's comprehensive scope. The decree "I am going to destroy them along with the earth" mirrors the scope of the corruption — what humanity has corrupted, the judgment will erase. The <em>Atra-hasis</em> flood narrative has the gods deciding on the flood after exhausting other plague-and-famine attempts to control human population; Genesis has no such incremental escalation — YHWH's single decree is made on the basis of moral assessment alone.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The ark (<em>tēḇāh</em>) is one of only two uses of this word in the OT — the other is Moses's basket-ark in the Nile (Exod 2:3,5), also coated with pitch. The word differs from the standard word for "ship" or "boat"; it describes a vessel designed for preservation rather than navigation. The pitch coating (<em>kōper</em>) shares its root with <em>kippēr</em> (to cover/atone/make propitiation) — the atonement-covering language of the Levitical sacrificial system. The structural parallel: the ark's pitch-covering protects from the flood waters; the sacrificial covering (kipper) protects from divine judgment. Utnapishtim's boat in the Gilgamesh epic is similarly coated with six measures of pitch, inside and outside.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>The ark's dimensions — 300 × 50 × 30 cubits — are remarkably similar to the proportions of modern cargo vessels. A cubit of approximately 18 inches gives dimensions of 450 × 75 × 45 feet, or roughly 137 × 23 × 14 meters. The 6:1 length-to-width ratio is the standard barge ratio for stability and capacity in flat-bottomed vessels. The ANE parallels are instructive by contrast: Utnapishtim's ark in the Gilgamesh epic is a perfect cube (60 cubits each side), and the <em>Atra-hasis</em> ark appears circular — both are clearly stylized/symbolic shapes. Genesis's dimensions are the most architecturally realistic of the ancient flood-ark traditions.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>The ark's structural details — "a roof, leaving below the roof an opening one cubit high all around; put a door in the side… lower, middle and upper decks" — reflect the multi-deck construction of ancient river craft. The "opening one cubit high all around" has been interpreted as a ventilation gap just below the roof — a practical detail consistent with ancient enclosed-vessel construction. The three decks (<em>taḥtiyyim šĕniyyim ûšĕlišiyyim</em>, lower, second, and third) mirror the three-tier ANE cosmological model (underworld, earth, heaven) and the three-compartment tabernacle (outer court, holy place, holy of holies).</p>""",
    "17": """<p>"Everything on earth will perish" (<em>kōl ʾăšer-bāʾāreṣ yigwāʿ</em>) — the breath-of-life withdrawal is the inverse of 2:7 (YHWH breathing life into Adam) and 6:3 (Spirit's animating presence). The flood is an un-creation: the creature who received the breath of life will lose it; the creation that emerged from the watery deep will return to the watery deep. The language of cosmic reversal — heavens, waters, breath of life, land creatures — systematically undoes the creative work of days 2-6. The Noahic covenant of 9:8-17 will then be a re-creation covenant, establishing that YHWH will never again un-create in this way.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>The first use of the word "covenant" (<em>bĕrît</em>) in the Bible — "I will establish my covenant (<em>bĕrîtî</em>) with you" — is remarkable for its context: it comes within the decree of universal judgment. The covenant is YHWH's unilateral commitment to Noah before the ark is built, before the flood comes, before the sacrifice is offered. The verb <em>hăqîmōtî</em> (I will establish/confirm) is later used for the formal ratification of covenants already implicit (9:9; 17:7,19,21; Exod 6:4); it suggests the covenant with Noah is the first explicit articulation of a bond that creation itself implies. The family structure of covenant-inclusion (you, your sons, your wife, your sons' wives) establishes the household as the covenant unit.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>The command to bring "two of all living creatures" (<em>ûmikkol-haḥay</em>) into the ark to "keep them alive" (<em>lĕhaḥăyôt</em>) is the ecological preservation mandate embedded within the judgment. The animals that YHWH created "good" (1:21,25) and blessed with fruitfulness (1:22) will be preserved through the judgment, not lost in it. The survival of animal species through the flood establishes the Noahic covenant's scope: it will be made with "every living creature" (9:10,12), not only with humanity. The ark is the instrument of creation-preservation, not merely human survival.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>The animals "will come to you to be kept alive" — the passive construction places the initiative with YHWH, not Noah. Noah does not gather the animals; they come to him. This divine orchestration of the ark-loading is the counterpart to the creation-narrative's "God brought them to Adam" for naming (2:19). What YHWH brought to Adam to be named, YHWH now brings to Noah to be preserved — the pattern of divine initiative in animal-human relationships continues through the crisis.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>The command to store food for the ark's occupants reflects the practical logistics of ancient animal husbandry: extended sea voyages required massive food stores. Archaeological evidence from Bronze Age Egypt and Mesopotamia shows meticulous grain and food storage in large vessels, consistent with the kind of provisioning the ark required. The food-provision command also echoes the creation mandate of 1:29-30 — both humans and animals were given vegetation for food in the original creation; the ark's food store preserves the same creation-order feeding pattern through the flood.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>Noah's comprehensive obedience — "Noah did everything just as God commanded him" (<em>wayyaʿaś Nōaḥ kĕkōl ʾăšer ṣiwwāh ʾōtô ʾĕlōhîm kēn ʿāśāh</em>) — is the foundational qualification of the covenant-servant. The same formula describes Moses's execution of the tabernacle instructions (Exod 39:43; 40:16) and Joshua's execution of the conquest commands. Comprehensive obedience — "everything (<em>kōl</em>) just as God commanded" — is the mark of the covenant-faithful servant, in contrast to the "every imagination of the heart was only evil all the time" (<em>kol-yēṣer maḥšĕḇôt libbô raq raʿ kol-hayyôm</em>) of the corrupt generation (v5). The contrast between "all evil all the time" and "all things just as commanded" is the narrative's moral bookend.</p>"""
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis')
    before_count = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    merge_comm(existing, GENESIS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis', existing)

    result = load_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis')
    after_count = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Verses added: {after_count - before_count}')
    for ch in [4, 5, 6]:
        ck = str(ch)
        n = len(result.get(ck, {}))
        print(f'  Ch {ch}: {n} verses present')
    total_chs = len(result)
    total_vv = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Genesis context total: {total_chs} chapters, {total_vv} verses')
    print('Genesis 4–6 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
